<br>
           PROTE[S]TER HONORS VETS<br>
           Wed Nov 13 14:00:30 US/Eastern 1996 <br>
&lt;snipped for conciseness&gt;<br>
Those of us who think the Vietnam war was a terrible mistake<br>
should carefully consider how we feel about the Americans who fought there. During the war there was animosity against them from the protest community. Those of us who were draft bait know that these people were victims of the war too. Even the ones who volunteered. Their government told them they were fighting for freedom at a time when that government was trusted. <br>
           <br>
We should take that thought one step further and realize that many individual soldiers were fighting for their country. They did heroic things for their country. They died for their country. A sacrafice for a cause you believe is right is no less a sacrafice because ten years later it turns out not to be right. Those soldiers' intent was to fight for their country and that intent was noble.<br><br>
-- tcrenshaw@mail.wallowa.k12.or.us (Terry Crenshaw) <br><br>
Cook Barela: <br><br>
Our company was running an operation across the Tra Khuc River from an area known as The Horseshoe. Every day we were fighting and taking casualties - hit and run bullshit. At night we had at least one ambush outside the perimeter, seeing as there was much enemy activity in the area. <br><br>
This one guy let it slip, one morning, that he had let several of the enemy pass through the ambush of the night before. He didn't open fire. My Commanding Officer wasn't one to mince words. He screamed at the man that if any of his buddies got hit that day, it would be his fault. The whole company heard this one sided conversation. It was war, all right. Your story last night, about you allowing the NVA soldier to take flight, reminded me of this incident.<br><br>
You remarked in your story how you hoped that the enemy soldier had made it through and was still alive. <br><br>
I think that alot of Americans who overlook the suffering of the Vietnamese people and who can't figure out why the enemy fought us so hard have always been unable to put themselves in the shoes of &quot;the other guy&quot;.<br><br>
Gerry Ney related how a village was shot up. How many times did we see and, yes, partake in the same sort of thing? What troubles me is that we EXPECTED the Vietnamese people to ACCEPT it, without question. Would we accept it here? <br><br>
What troubles me also is that many of my brother vets feel that &quot;college professors&quot; and the rest of the folks back home did not have a right to an opinion about how they were being represented by other Americans in the war. The media was blamed. To deny people the right to protest or to question the legitimacy of the war because &quot;they were not there&quot;, in my opinion is to be repressive - the very thing we were supposedly fighting against. &quot;The light at the end of the tunnel&quot;. Remember that bullshit? We ALL got it broke off in our asses. We trusted them, didn't we? <br><br>
I invite you to put yourself in the shoes of the NVA soldier whom you let slip away. I suggest to you that if he did survive he has not forgotten the incident either. And as he reflects on that incident in the jungle he thinks about you, and hopes that you made it also.<br><br>

<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


